result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica M. Udd was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse Assessments, Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jessica M. Udd in court with attorney Anne Renc on behalf of Acalia Halverson. Defendant Jessica M. Udd in custody. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

11:02 a.m.  Court calls case.
Atty Knaapen states the apperances. 

Plea questionnaire/Agreement filed.
Prosecutor states plea agreement.
State has complied with the victim witness notification; no victims appear today.
Attorney for Defendant concurs with agreement stated.

Defendant enters a plea of: 
Count 1 - No contest
Count 2 - DRI

Court questions Defendant regarding plea.
Court informs Defendant of Constitutional Rights. Court advises Defendant of Elements State must prove for the Charge.
Court questions Attorney for Defendant.
Court finds Defendant's Plea is freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.
Attorneys stipulate that there is factual basis for the charge(s).

BY THE COURT:
Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charge(s).
Court finds the defendant guilty on Count 1 and Count 2 is DRI.  Clerk directed to enter Judgment of Conviction this date.

Atty Knaapen makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Atty Renc makes sentencing arguments to the Court. 
Defendant does not wish to make a statement prior to sentencing.

BY THE COURT:
Count 1 -
150 days in County Jail - STAYED
Placed on probation for 24 months
AODA & comply with treatment recommendations; unless recently completed then sign release for agent to verify.
Maintain absolute sobriety with regards to alcohol.
Do not possess or consume alcohol or be on premises where alcohol is served/sold.
Do not have ABUSIVE contact with the following persons/places:   Eugene Slattery.
Participate in any counseling recommended by the agent.
Pay Court costs which will include the DNA surcharge/Domestic Abuse Surcharge
Write letter of apology to Eugene Slattery.
Provide DNA Sample
71 days jail credit 
If revoked then will have to sit the remaining days in jail with no home detention.  If revoked Huber privileges are granted pursuant to Sec. 303.08(1) Stats. and subject to the rules of the Portage County Sheriff's Department.

Count 2 - DRI

Attorney Acalia Halverson in court.  Defendant Jessica M. Udd appeared by video. Prosecuting Atty Elizabeth R. Constable appeared for State of Wisconsin.
Attorney/Defendant received copy of criminal complaint.
Court informs defendant of charges and maximum penalties.
Attorney/Defendant waives reading of complaint.

NOT GUILTY pleas entered.

BY THE COURT:  Bond continued.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for July 20, 2015 at 10:00 am.

Do not have direct/indirect contact with the following persons/places:  *Eugene Slattery  *Unless the victim goes to CAP Services to get a Family Safety Plan and then files the form with the Clerk of Courts and District Attorney. 
Do not possess or consume alcohol or be on premises where alcohol is served/sold as its primary business except within scope of your employment.
Participate in the Portage County Pre-Trial Supervision Program and comply with the requirements for reporting, assessment, and programming.

ADA Cass Cousins appears in Court.  
Defendant appears from jail by video.

ADA Cousins states facts for anticipated charges of Battery-Domestic.
Court finds probable cause that a crime has been committed and that this defendant committed it.
Court informs Defendant right to an attorney and/or Public Defender.

State requests a $1,000 cash bond with conditions as stated.
Court advises defendant of right to make a statement.
